  :prose
"Feel is timing. The player perceives a game as fair when their
input has a small window of forgiveness. Impossible-to-fail feels
cheap; frame-perfect-or-die feels punishing. The sweet spot is
usually 4-10 frames of slack, invisible to conscious thought but
felt in the thumbs.

This appendix catalogs the timing windows used in real arcade games
and gives you `world/after`-based skeletons for each.

## Coyote time

After walking off a ledge, still-airborne player can jump for N
frames.

```scheme
;; 6-frame coyote time.
(define grounded? #t) (define was-grounded? #t) (define coyote 0)
(when (and was-grounded? (not grounded?)) (set! coyote 6))
(when (> coyote 0) (set! coyote (- coyote 1)))
(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (when (or grounded? (> coyote 0))
    (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
    (set! coyote 0)))
(set! was-grounded? grounded?)
```

Recommended: 4-8 frames (0.07-0.13 seconds). Below 4 = harsh. Above
8 = feels like cheating.

## Jump buffer

Pressed jump before landing? Fire on land.

```scheme
;; 8-frame jump buffer.
(define buffer 0)
(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (if grounded?
      (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
      (set! buffer 8)))
(when (and grounded? (> buffer 0))
  (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
  (set! buffer 0))
(when (> buffer 0) (set! buffer (- buffer 1)))
```

Recommended: 6-10 frames. Feels responsive without misfiring.

## Dash cancel

After a dash, N frames of immunity to certain inputs.

```scheme
(define dashing 0)
(define dash-cd 0)   ;; cooldown
(when (input/pressed? 'b)
  (when (= dash-cd 0)
    (entity/set-vel! p (* 8 heading-x) 0)
    (set! dashing 6)
    (set! dash-cd 30)))
(when (> dashing 0) (set! dashing (- dashing 1)))
(when (> dash-cd 0) (set! dash-cd (- dash-cd 1)))
```

6 frames of dash (0.1 sec), 30 frames cooldown (0.5 sec). Player
can't spam dash, but the dash itself is snappy.

## Attack window / combo timing

Chained attacks link if the next input arrives within N frames of
the previous attack's animation start.

```scheme
(define last-attack 0)
(define combo-count 0)
(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (if (< (- (world/frame) last-attack) 30)
      (set! combo-count (+ combo-count 1))
      (set! combo-count 1))
  (set! last-attack (world/frame))
  (audio/play (case combo-count
                ((1) 'attack-1) ((2) 'attack-2) ((3) 'attack-3)
                (else 'attack-finish))))
```

30 frames = 0.5 sec. If player presses attack again within half a
second, they chain. Combo 4+ triggers finisher.

## Grace period after damage

After taking damage, player is briefly invulnerable.

```scheme
(define invuln 0)
;; On damage:
(when (and enemy-hit? (= invuln 0))
  (entity/damage! p 1)
  (set! invuln 60)   ;; 1 second invincibility
  (world/camera-shake! 5 0.9))
(when (> invuln 0) (set! invuln (- invuln 1)))
```

60 frames (1 sec) is standard 'i-frames' in fighting games. Prevents
combo death after one mistake.

## Input echo / hold detection

Distinguish a tap (short press) from a hold (long press).

```scheme
(define press-frame 0)
(define press-active? #f)
(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (set! press-frame (world/frame))
  (set! press-active? #t))
(when (and press-active? (not (input/down? 'a)))
  ;; Just released.
  (let ((hold-duration (- (world/frame) press-frame)))
    (cond
      ((< hold-duration 6)  (do-tap))
      ((< hold-duration 30) (do-hold))
      (else                 (do-long-hold))))
  (set! press-active? #f))
```

Under 6 frames = tap. 6-30 = hold. Above = long-hold. Three
distinct actions from one button by measuring release time.

## Double-tap detection

Two taps within N frames.

```scheme
(define last-tap 0)
(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (if (< (- (world/frame) last-tap) 15)
      (do-double-tap)
      (do-single-tap))
  (set! last-tap (world/frame)))
```

15 frames (0.25 sec) is a reasonable double-click window. Adjustable.

## Charge attack

Hold button N frames for a stronger attack.

```scheme
(define charge 0)
(when (input/down? 'a) (set! charge (+ charge 1)))
(when (and (not (input/down? 'a)) (> charge 0))
  (let ((strength (min 5 (quotient charge 20))))
    (fire-with-strength strength))
  (set! charge 0))
```

Every 20 held frames adds one strength level, capped at 5.

## Rhythm-game timing

Precise beat-locked input windows.

```scheme
;; Beat every 30 frames (2 beats/sec). Window is ±4 frames.
(define (rhythm-hit?)
  (let ((phase (modulo (world/frame) 30)))
    (or (< phase 4) (> phase 26))))

(when (input/pressed? 'a)
  (if (rhythm-hit?)
      (score-hit)
      (score-miss)))
```

4-frame window at 60 FPS = 66 ms — tight but forgiving.

## Common desktop tasks

**Long-press-to-confirm.** A shop's 'delete order' button requires
a hold to fire — prevents accidental clicks. Use hold-detection
above with `hold-duration > 60`.

**Double-click-to-fave.** A shop item can be favorited by double-
clicking. Use double-tap detection.

## Pitfalls

**Coyote fires on stairs.** Every frame the player might briefly
un-ground (stepping between tiles). Add a MINIMUM airborne-frames
check before starting coyote.

**Buffer replays after death.** Clear all input buffers on death
and respawn.

**Charge counter runs during pause menu.** Freeze charge counting
during any state that isn't 'play.

**Combo drops on ONE-frame miss.** Extend combo window by a
frame or two if playtest reveals combo drops too easily.

## The universal window sizes

Committed to memory:

- Frame-perfect (1 frame): only for expert-mode games. Bad default.
- Twitchy (2-3): responsive shooters.
- Comfortable (4-8): most action games. Default.
- Forgiving (9-15): family-friendly. Kids under 10.
- Cinematic (16+): narrative games where input is less about
  precision.

Every timing window in your game should be in one of these bands.
Playtest to pick the band for your audience.

## The one-line test

If your game feels bad, add 4 frames to your coyote and buffer
windows. Play again. Better? Keep. Worse? Revert. Almost every
feel bug is a timing window that's too tight.")
